<HEAD>Ruling Party Candidate Winning, But Lowest Margin in 60 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `At a...' with six grafs to UPDATE with PRI
chairman proclaiming victory in 27 states, Salinas comments on
credibility of vote count. Pick up 8th pvs, ``I believe...' Edits
to trim thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Preliminary figures from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s presidential election show the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate winning, but with the lowest margin in its six decades in office <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> figures obtained from a reliable source show <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> with 47.4 percent of the 4.5 million votes counted so far. <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> was second with 26.7 percent and <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> third with 20.7 percent. The 4.5 million votes counted are out of 11.7 million ballots reported so far to the commission. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has 38 million registered voters but no figures are available how many voted in Wednesday's election In addition to the presidency, 64 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats and 500 in the newly expanded Chamber of Deputies are at stake. A final vote count is not expected until Sunday. The early leak appeared designed to counter growing speculation that the ruling party, known as the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> for its initials in Spanish, had suffered a devastating loss. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, proclaimed a party victory in at least 27 of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 31 states and said opposition accusations of fraud were meant to confuse the electorate. `` The <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> is going to defend its legal and unobjectionable electoral triumph with all the means of the law. It is going to mobilize the force of all its organizations to combat the provocation and irresponsibility'' of the opposition, he said. A relaxed and smiling <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, meeting Friday night with foreign reporters, insisted that he was more concerned that the vote count be credible than with his margin of victory. `` Those results reflect real votes,'' he said. `` The results so far ratify this circumstance of plurality ... and a new political reality in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' He said opposition parties will be most visible in the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, where presumably would have a role in approving or blocking constitutional changes that require a two-thirds majority. At a news conference earlier Friday, <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> accused the government of delaying an announcement in order to falsify results. `` They are waiting to see how to disguise the figures,'' he said. `` I believe we won, but I do n't want to boast prematurely as my adversary has,'' he said of the victory claim by <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has changed. Totally changed. ... We will never have only one party again.'' <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> met earlier in the day and agreed to share their information on voting results in order to challenge government figures. He said they also agreed not to release figures publicly for the time being, because when the government finds out what information the opposition has, then officials will know which results they can `` dress up.'' No PRI presidential candidate since the party's founding in 1929 has won less than 70 percent of the vote. The slow count also is making evident splits within the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> between the 40-year-old <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> and the old-style politicians. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which controls the vote count, is headed by <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, who was among <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s chief rivals for the presidential nomination. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> has insisted throughout the campaign that he will introduce a new era in which opposition voices will be heard. <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> governor in the central state of <LOCATION> Michoacan </LOCATION> until his break with the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> last year, waged an unusually strong campaign that capitalized on widespread discontent with the hardships caused by six years of economic crisis. The leftist candidate is the son of the revered late President <PERSON> Lazaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>. In renouncing his own presidential hopes and endorsing <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> last spring, <PERSON> Heberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> of the rival <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> described the <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> movement as a `` phenomenon.'' <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> appeared ready to concede losses to <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Michoacan </LOCATION>, the central state of <LOCATION> Morelos </LOCATION> and in the Federal District, the core of the sprawling <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> metropolitan area. A fourth <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> victory could come in the populous state of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which abuts the Federal District on three sides. The vote count made available to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> also showed <PERSON> Gumersino </PERSON> <PERSON> Magana </PERSON> <PERSON> Negrete </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 0.95 percent of the vote and <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibarra </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Piedra </PERSON> of the radical <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 0.4 percent. Most districts recorded so far are urban, where <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> are strongest. The Salinas de Gortari percentage could be expected to rise slightly with reports from rural district where the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> is traditionally strong. <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said soon after the election that technical difficulties with a new computer system delayed the returns. He later blamed bad weather. The government says the elections were peaceful and clean. <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> officials have said charges by opposition parties that the balloting was fraudulent were a publicity move. The Assembly for Effective Suffrage, a civic watchdog group, recorded 1,100 cases of voting irregularities ranging from ballot-stuffing to tampering with voter registration rolls.
