<HEAD>No Punishment For Smokers Violating Norway's Anti-Smoking Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Smokers will not be punished for violating <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s tough new anti-smoking law, a government official said. But operators of restaurants, hotels or other public areas risk fines if people are found smoking where they should n't, <PERSON> Trine </PERSON> <PERSON> Lind </PERSON>, information secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. The law went into effect July 1, but its provisions were only set at a cabinet meeting on Friday. Maximum fines were not immediately published. The law bans smoking outside special smoking sections in public transportion, theater lobbies, banks, post offices and work places. The government has said it wants to make <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> tobacco-free by the year 2000. Four out of 10 adult Norwegians now smoke.
