<SECOND>PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aegis System Got Poor Marks In GAO Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Aegis air defense system, used by the cruiser <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> last week to track and shoot down an Iranian passenger jet, may not have been adequately tested before it was deployed, according to a classified review by a congressional watchdog agency. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study concluded that the $ 1 billion system has not proven its ability to discriminate among targets, said congressional sources who have seen the document. They spoke Friday on condition they not be named. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> review started last year and did not mention last week's destruction of <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> flight 655 that killed all 290 people aboard The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> fired at the airliner after mistaking it for an Iranian F-14. Pentagon officials have said the Aegis system was not malfunctioning. A `` minor degradation'' of the Aegis radar was repaired before the ship entered the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> last month, they said. Aegis, named for the shield of Zeus in Greek mythology, is a complex mix of radars and computers. It was developed as the main component of protection for <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> surface ships against enemy ships and planes. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is building a fleet of Aegis cruisers, of which the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> is the third. The service is also using some components of the Aegis system aboard other surface ships. The system was first deployed in 1983. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> review looked at the Aegis testing program before the system went into service, said the sources. The study criticized a series of 1984 tests in which the Aegis system tracked 11 targets and guided the firing of weapons which hit 10, the sources said. At one point, two targets were fired upon at the same time. The 1984 test program was set up specifically to answer complaints from <PERSON> Aegis </PERSON> critics who argued that the system needed more realistic tests. But the tests were set up so carefully they did not approximate a `` real-life'' combat environment, the sources quoted the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report as saying. In other developments Friday: _ President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the issue of whether to pay compensation for the families of those killed is `` under consideration. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said there were `` still some open questions'' on the issue. _ Sen <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should adopt a new stance in the Iran-Iraq war `` equidistant'' from the two warring countries `` I do believe that we'd be much better served in trying to end the war if we were really in a position of condemning both attacks by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and also condemning the chemical warfare being conducted against innocent people by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>,'' he said. _ Pentagon officials said they are awaiting results of an investigation to learn why the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> missed air traffic communications and other clues indicating that the jet was a civilian plane and not an F-14 fighter, as officers aboard the ship believed Iranian officials have said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> systems should have been able to monitor 21 minutes of conversation in English between the jetliner and the airport control tower in <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>. But Pentagon spokesmen said they were not sure <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces were monitoring, or were able to monitor, air traffic control communications at the time of the incident. `` We are looking forward to an analysis of the tapes to help clarify the issue,' said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumann </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman.
</TEXT>
