<HEAD>Pinochet Announces Presidential Vote Within 90 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALCAHUANO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President and military leader <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said a plebiscite to choose the president for 1989-97 will take place within the next 90 days. He is expected to be the only candidate. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> also said Friday he already has a platform for his next presidential term, but he refused to disclose it because the opposition `` would copy it.'' `` The plebiscite is near. There are less than 90 days left,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> told an audience of 16,000 supporters in this southern port city 330 miles from <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. The 72-year-old army commander has ruled this <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nation since a 1973 coup. His remark was the most precise indication so far of a date for the ballot. According to the 1980 military-drafted Constitution, the nation's next presiddnt will be picked in a plebiscite in which Chileans will only be able to vote yes or no on a single candidate nominated by the heads of the three armed services and the national police. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> himself will participate in the nomination as commander-in-chief of the army and is considered the most likely nominee. He is allowed by the Constitution to seek re-election and has clearly indicated he intends to do so. If voters approve the nominee, he will serve for eight years starting in March 1989. If rejected, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> will remain in power until 1990, and an open election would take place. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> blasted opposition leaders seeking support from the international community as `` traitors.'' He said some critics who recently were given limited access to television are going too far in their broadscast remarks. `` When those bad Chileans make insults on television, because they know we are in a democracy and we wo n't do anything to them, let's tell them that our patience has limits and that they could soon discover those limits,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> warned. He predicted an overwhelming victory in the upcoming plebiscite and said of his opponents, `` We will wipe them out.''
