<HEAD>Senators Urge Reagan to Divert Water from Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Falling water levels on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> that have stranded barges are threatening to trigger a regional water fight on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, pitting southern senators and others against Great Lakes lawmakers. On Friday, Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Tenn </LOCATION>., asked President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for an emergency diversion of water from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> and 12 other senators urged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in a letter to direct the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> to increase the flow of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> water to the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Waterway </LOCATION> and the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> from 3,000 to 10,000 cubic feet per second for 100 days. The action triggered immediate opposition from several <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> lawmakers led by Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, who said it would be illegal unless approved by all the Great Lakes governors. And in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, Justice Minister <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Hnatyshyn </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s ambassador in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotlieb </PERSON>, would deliver a formal notice to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> saying that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is unalterably opposed to any diversion. <PERSON> Hnatyshyn </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> can veto any diversion proposal as a result of several treaties. `` We control our resources,'' he said. `` We will continue to control our resources.'' <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> said the drought has pushed water levels on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> three feet lower than they have been since 1872, when officials first began keeping records. As many as 3,000 barges are stranded, with the loss to the barge and towing industry possibly exceeding $ 60 million, he said. `` Communities along the river face the prospects of drinking water shortages and drinking water pollution because of the drought,'' said <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>. He said the diversion would raise the level of the river by one foot in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and six inches in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> and only lower the level of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huron </LOCATION> by one inch. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said the Great Lakes states are hurting as well. He said Great Lakes water levels have fallen two feet in the past 18 months and are likely to continue to fall. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> also said any action to divert the water would be illegal because the 1986 Water Resources Development Act bars diversion unless it is approved by all of the Great Lakes governors. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has set a limit on how much water can be diverted without its permission. <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> said he believes the president has the authority to take the action as commander in chief in a national emergency. Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., said corps officials he has talked to do not believe they have the legal authority to take the action or that it would do much good He said they believe that reducing the loads of barges would be more effective. Lake levels have dropped by 30 inches in the past two years, said Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich. Added Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., `` Diversion of water from the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> into the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> may damage navigation, hydroelectric generation and the environment Signing the letter to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> urging the diversion were <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> and Sens. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Bumpers </PERSON>, D-Ark., <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky., <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stennis </PERSON>, D-Miss., <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Ky., <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Ill., <PERSON> John </PERSON> Others joining <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> in speaking against the action were Sens. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>, R-Minn., and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>, R-Wis
