<HEAD>Caribbean Leaders Say US Drug Fight Should Not Interfere In Region</HEAD>
<HEAD>By HELEN J. SIMON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leaders of 13 Caribbean nations have accused the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> of interfering in their region's affairs as it cracks down on drugs and urged President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to halt the meddling. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> and Common Market _ ended five days of talks Friday without agreeing on <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s coup but they agreed to work toward eliminating obstacles to regional trade by Oct. 1. The leaders drafted a letter to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> saying that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was overstepping its jurisdiction by investigating alleged drug traffickers in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. The contents of the letter were not revealed, but <LOCATION> Antigua </LOCATION> Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> said it would be signed by the <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION> secretary general to represent all the leaders. Bird announced it would protest what the leaders considered a `` derogation'' of their local laws and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> violations of their sovereignty as the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration seeks to win favor in an election year. Some of the leaders criticized <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> for making the announcement prematurely. Prime Minister <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Grenadines </ORGANIZATION> said it was `` bad manners.'' Others stressed their traditionally close ties with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and said it had not intervened directly in their affairs. Bird, reading from a communique drafted by the leaders, said they also `` reaffirmed their total commitment to the fight against ... all illegal trafficking in drugs.'' `` They expressed their willingness to ccoperate with other countries for the establishment of internationally acceptable mechanisms to bring offenders to justice,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> has long been a source and an important conduit for drugs coming into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Cocaine from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> traditionaly passes through <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> ports before entering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Much marijuana is also grown in the area. From the start of the meeting Monday, it was apparent the leaders were unlikely to reach unanimous agreement, as required by <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION> rules, on what position to take on the <LOCATION> Haitian </LOCATION> military government that ousted President <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> in a coup June 19. They debated options ranging from revoking <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s status as an observer on four <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION> standing committees to simply issuing a strong statement denouncing the coup. The leaders were more successful when talking about intra-regional trade. The leaders agreed to remove all trade obstacles, such as stamp duties and import licenses, by Oct. 1 and to study a request by the smaller countries to protect 23 items they consider too fragile to compete with imports. Trade and industry ministers will meet before the Oct. 1 deadline to decide which items should be excluded and for how long. <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION>, established in 1973 to promote regional trade and set common positions on international events, includes <LOCATION> Antigua-Barbuda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belize </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montserrat </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kitts-Nevis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Grenadines </ORGANIZATION> and Trinidad-Tobago.
