<HEAD>Cruise Ship Officer Rescues Woman From Drowning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sylvie Mullaly and Lars Kragelund are cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NAN HERLIHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cruise ship officer stripped to his shorts and leapt more than 50-feet into choppy night seas to rescue a drowning woman, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. The woman either fell or jumped off the Scandinavian Sky cruise ship 11 miles east of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> Thursday night, said Petty Officer <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sylvie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullaly </PERSON>, 31, of <LOCATION> Cocoa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, and her rescuer, Staff Capt. <PERSON> Lars </PERSON> <PERSON> Kragelund </PERSON>, were treated and released from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> following the ships return, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Mullaly </PERSON>, who works at a topless nightclub in <LOCATION> Cocoa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, is under investigation for possible intoxication, <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said. An investigation of the entire incident, including the ship's safety procedures, is underway, he said. Ms. <PERSON> Mullaly </PERSON> was spotted bobbing in the water as the ship returned from a daylong cruise, <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kragelund </PERSON> raced from the ship's wheelhouse, peeling off his uniform as he ran and dived from a ship's rail, he said. As he swam to the woman, the ship's crew assumed `` man overboard'' alert stations and the vessel swung in a wide circle around the couple, <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said. `` Apparently they were retrieved from the water via ladder. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> headed to the scene but turned back when we found out they had her'' out of the water, he said. The Scandinavian Sky is owned by Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Escape </ORGANIZATION> <ORG