<HEAD>US Cruiser Had Radar Malfunction In June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile cruiser that shot down an Iranian passenger jet it mistook for a fighter plane was out of action last month because its radar malfunctioned, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. But a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the breakdown on the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vincennes </ORGANIZATION> in June was only a `` minor degradation'' and had no bearing on Sunday's disaster that left 290 dead in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say the billion-dollar warship's high-tech radar system received signals from the <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> A300 identifying it as an Iranian F-14 fighter coming in for an attack. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> said all 290 people aboard were killed. The breakdown was reported on June 13 by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, although gulf-based <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials refused then to confirm that the problem lay in the computerized system, called Aegis. The Aegis system of computer-linked radar and weapons is designed primarily for defending a naval fleet in the open ocean from air and missile attack. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> says it can detect, identify and head off a threat developing hundreds of miles away. The 9,600-ton <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> arrived in the gulf May 27, the first of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Aegis cruisers to be assigned to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval force in the waterway. It was assigned to patrol in the southern gulf, but by about June 10 it was anchored off <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sources said it was undergoing repair work on the radar system that lies at the core of its capabilities. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in the gulf, asked about the reported breakdown at that time, said only that the ship was in port for `` maintenance upkeep,'' the result of an unspecified problem. Officials here refused comment Friday, but a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, Lt. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Cullin </PERSON>, confirmed the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> had been down with a `` minor degradation'' of its radar system. He said there was no connection between that and the shooting down of the Iranian jetliner. `` The problem had absolutely no bearing on the whole incident,'' he said in a telephone interview. `` It -LRB- the cruiser -RRB- was never less than 100 percent up on any mission capability, including anti-aircraft warfare.'' He said he could not confirm that the ship was out of action for 16 days, as reported by the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cullin </PERSON> said the problem had actually been detected during the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>' 32-day voyage from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, where it arrived May 22. A necessary replacement part was flown to the ship and installed by the ship's own crew, he said, `` and the ship was back up on line by June 6.'' He said he did not know why the ship was then off the line again, spending at least three days around June 10-13 at anchor outside <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, before it returned to its duty station in the southern gulf. Some of the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>' crew said they were puzzled why the ship had been ordered to make a rush departure from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> after only 90 hours of port preparation, and on arrival spent five days in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, `` sailing in circles'' as one officer described it, before entering the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>. Many <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships, especially those with sophisticated electronics and other equipment, have civlian experts, known as `` tech reps,'' aboard to maintain and repair the gear. Most are employees of the manufacturers. There were no such representatives aboard the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>. Its officers told journalists who rode the ship into the gulf that the crew was fully capable of maintaining and repairing the ship's complicated systems The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> was riding at anchor off <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> for a third day Friday, but two other warships that contributed data to the investigation of the jetliner incident, the frigate <PERSON> Elmer </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> and the missile frigate <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sides </PERSON>, returned to duty in the gulf. Both had been nearby when the aircraft was shot down. The disaster followed a clash involving the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Elmer </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> and some Iranian speedboats, two of which were sunk, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. Computer tapes from the warships are being sent back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for analysis at the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Surface warfare Center in <LOCATION> Dahlgren </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources said they could offer no indication of when a team of six military investigators sent here to investigate the incident would complete their task and return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> The team, headed by Rear Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogarty </PERSON>, arrived here on Tuesday with orders to deliver a report in 15 days if possible.
