> Prague </LOCATION>. Western reporters asked <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, who attended a three-day economic conference that ended Thursday, whether the time had not come for <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> to be rehabilitated. He replied: `` The rehabilitation of <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, that is a question for <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. I do not intend to deal with the internal problems of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. As far as I know the Czechoslovak party does not intend to deal with that.'' <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, now 66, said in an Austrian Television interview broadcast Thursday that the current leadership in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> should adopt <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. Most are similar to reforms <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> introduced here 20 years ago.
