<HEAD>With PM-Airliner Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> downing of an Iranian jetliner has prompted airlines flying over the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> to seek ways to avoid military confrontations. The issue topped the agenda when technical experts from six major airlines operating passenger flights in the gulf area held a regular meeting at the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Thursday's session also was attended by an official of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency that on July 13 is to consider <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s request for an investigation into the tragedy. Association officials would not comment when asked about the possibility of rerouting flights. They also declined to talk about reported complaints of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s contradicting plane instructions from civilian air controllers. `` We reviewed procedures in the gulf area to see if the airlines could help improve civil-military coordination,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, head of the group's technical department. `` We saw a number of areas where we could be helpful,'' he said in a telephone interview. He declined to elaborate. Asked whether rerouting was discussed, he said: `` Any routing changes through the gulf is a matter for <ORGANIZATION> ICAO </ORGANIZATION> _ the governments.'' But the association, an industry association grouping most of the world's airlines, seemed certain to be considering the idea, too. `` We are in close touch with <ORGANIZATION> ICAO </ORGANIZATION> on technical aspects,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. <ORGA