<HEAD>Death Toll Rises To 115, Reports Say 5 Million Marooned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Torrential rains swelled rivers and sparked flooding that crushed homes and capsized boats, marooning millions of people and killing up to 115, authorities said. The <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> warned that the flooding that has plagued the country for the past week could worsen in the next two days. The board said in a statement issued Friday that all rivers in the <LOCATION> Brahmaputra </LOCATION> basin were rising from the rain and the onrush of waters from northeastern Indian states. The army was called out Friday to assist with rescue opertions. Press reports said as many as 5 million people were marooned in northeastern districts. `` The number of marooned people is so huge you can not bring all of them to safer places,'' said an official in the town of <LOCATION> Sunamganj </LOCATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Sunamganj </LOCATION> is 112 miles northeast of the capital at <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>. Vice President <PERSON> Nurul </PERSON> <PERSON> Islam </PERSON> flew to the <LOCATION> Sunamganj </LOCATION> area by helicopter Friday to assess flood damage. The aircraft was unable to land because no suitable dry ground could be found, an aide said today on condition of anonymity. Twenty-four more deaths occurred Friday, according to local government officials and newspaper reports, raising the unofficial death toll to at least 115. The government confirmed 10 new deaths and said its official count stood at 60. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION>, an independent English-language daily, and <ORGANIZATION> Ittefaq </ORGANIZATION>, a Bengali-language daily, blamed the deaths on houses collapsing and boats capsizing. Most of the deaths were reported in the northeast, which has been hardest hit by the floods. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, one of the poorest nations in the world with a population of more than 105 million, often suffers flooding during the annual monsoon rain season. Its low-lying land is vulnerable because not enough dams have been constructed on major rivers to control water flow. Press reports said rescue efforts were hampered by relentless rain. Thousands of people were trapped on rooftops or high ground without food, press reports said. The <ORGANIZATION> Ittefaq </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said there were reports of outbreaks of diarrhea and other water-borne diseases because of a shortage of pure drinking water. The northeastern tea-growing district of <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION> was all but cut off from the rest of the country Friday when the main highway bridge washed away. Air service to the region was suspended earlier in the week when runways flooded. In <LOCATION> Hobiganj </LOCATION>, just southwest of <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION>, a tributary of the <LOCATION> Brahmaputra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> was flowing more than 5 feet above flood level, the highest in memory, the <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> Moulvibazar </LOCATION> in the district just south of <LOCATION> Sylhet </LOCATION>, town leaders urged residents to leave for higher ground as the town's protective embankment threatened to cave in, officials there said
