<HEAD>Assembly Passes Laws To Subpoena Ex-President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> today passed two laws that could force former President <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON> to testify on charges of corruption that allegedly occurred during his seven-year tenure. Government party officials said they would ask President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo to veto the laws approved by the opposition-controlled legislature. The proposals were passed 164-125, with three absentions. If vetoed, the bills likely would die because the opposition lacks the two-thirds legislative majority needed to override a presidential veto. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s three predominant opposition parties together control 166 seats in the 299-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> criticized the proposals and said <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> would certainly veto them. Party officials argued the bills are unconstitutional. `` It is highly regrettable that the opposition rammed the law bills through the Assembly in disregard of our repeated warnings that they would be vetoed,'' <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> floor leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoon-hwan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Won-ki </PERSON>, floor leader for the <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition group, said he doubted <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> would veto the bills. `` I do n't think President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> would veto the bills. He has repeatedly promised that there would be no sanctuary in investigating past corruption and irregularities,'' the opposition leader said. The legislation contains a provision that empowers the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to subpoena witnesses with writs of arraignment issued by courts of law. Opposition politicians said such a law is needed to compel all witnesses to testify in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s huge government corruption case. They said privately that the main targets of the laws are <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> and his family. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> and other top government officials maintain that they would support efforts to ferret out all past corruption and irregularities under <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> but the president oppose any moves to make the Chun testify or stand trial. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, whose term ended in February, has come under public fire for alleged involvement in large-scale financial scandals. One of his brothers, <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyung-hwan </PERSON>, was arrested in March for embezzling millions of dollars. Several parliamentary committees were organized this week to look into alleged corruption and other problems under <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>. One committee is charged with probing a 1980 anti-government uprising in the southern city of <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> that left nearly 200 dead and more than 800 others injured, according to official count. Opposition and dissident groups allege that <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, along with <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, helped mastermind the brutal suppression of the uprising.
