, allowed new political parties and eased a ban on travel to mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Still to be changed is the parliamentary system in which mainland Chinese Nationalists hold a majority of seats to back the party's claim that it remains the rightful ruler of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teng-hui </PERSON>, who was acclaimed the first native Taiwanese party chairman Friday, has vowed to continue the process of democratic change and liberalization but has moved cautiously in past months as he has sought to consolidate power. The new members of the advisory committee, proposed by <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> and approved by the congress, include five of seven octagenarians on the Central Standing Committee. Three media executives on the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> who have said they want to give way to a younger leadership also were named to the advisory panel. But Premier <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo-hwa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang-huan </PERSON>, secretary to the president, were not named to the advisory group. The two 74-year-olds are influential conservatives and liberals fear they could block reforms. `` This will be a very conservative restructuring,'' said political journalist <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON>. But he added that the conservative old-guard's power base was dwindling and younger members would likely be more willing to speak up. The 1,209 congress delegates will elect a 180-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. For the first time, the vote will not be limited to candidates proposed by the party. The new <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will meet Thursday to name the new Central Standing Committee. A Cabinet overhaul is expected later.
