<HEAD>Government Proposes Regional Black Councils</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has proposed the creation of regional legislative councils to address matters related solely to blacks. Anti-apartheid activists condemned the proposal. Blacks would elect members to the regional councils under the proposed Extension of Political Participation Bill, which was published Friday in the official Government Gazette. The bill did not specify how many councils would be established. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> would have the power to veto bills passed by the councils. Presently, blacks can vote only in municipal elections and in 10 homelands. Elected black officials are widely viewed in their communities as collaborators with the white-led government. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no representation in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and can not vote in national elections. Its 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. The proposed councils would have authority over regional matters concerning blacks such as education, welfare, local government and community development. `` It is the government's viewpoint that all communities should participate in the government process on the different levels,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON>, minister of constitutional development and planning. <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>, member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the proposal was `` one of those hopeless efforts to avoid the realities of the South African situation.'' `` The duplication of -LRB- government -RRB- structures to run this country has become totally absurd,'' she said. Anti-apartheid activists have rejected all the government's major political reform proposals in recent years, saying they entrench white domination and continue to divide political participation by race The government is seeking comment on the latest proposal before deciding whether it will be introduced in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> said.
