<SECOND>PM-Burma,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Lift Curfew Imposed After Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities today lifted a dusk-to-dawn curfew that was imposed in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> after thousands of students rioted in the streets on June 21, state radio said. A ban on public gatherings also was lifted, the broadcast said. According to the government, six policemen and three civilians were killed in the rioting. The violence erupted after university students pressed demands, including release of colleagues detained in earlier protests, and the government responded by closing the schools. The government said that on Thursday and Friday, it freed all 784 people detained in connection with last month's riots and other rioting in March. Of those, 288 were students, it said. The government also for the first time made a concession to student demands, announcing on Friday that students expelled from schools for the March-June demonstrations will be readmitted.
