<SECOND>PM-China-Women,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Drafts Regulations To Protect Women Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has drafted comprehensive rules for women workers, barring them from hard physical labor and lengthening their maternity leaves, a report said today. The regulations also ban discrimination against women, but only if the work is deemed `` suitable for women workers,'' according to the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>. It said the regulations stipulate the kind and intensity of work suitable to women and bar them from labor-intensive jobs such as mining and leather-making. The criteria used in determining what jobs were suitable was not given. The regulations were drafted by the ministries of labor and public health, the <ORGANIZATION> All-China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> All-China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, and have been approved in principle by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the top executive body, the report said The rules guarantee women the right to refuse job assignments that could harm their health; allow one year of maternity leave with 90 paid days, up from the current 56; and guarantee rest periods for pregnant and menstruating women and those who have just had abortions. The newspaper did not comment on the possibility that the regulations would discourage employers from hiring women, who according to official reports already face greater difficulty than men in finding urban jobs. In the countryside most women do farmwork, although growing numbers of male peasants are leaving the land to work in small factories. The traditional belief that women are inferior to men is still deeply ingrained in Chinese society. The Guangming Daily reported last year that dozens of women graduates of <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> were rejected by the work units to which the state had assigned them. Some units said they did not employ women. Now that factory managers have been given the power to fire workers in recent years, women have been dismissed in larger numbers than men, official reports have said. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said the new regulations `` contain clear stipulations that all working units suitable for women workers should not reject female job applicants on any pretext.'' It did not say what sanctions, if any, would be applied against employers found guilty of discrimination. Chinese law already bars women from working in mines, but thousands are estimated to do so because mining often is the best-paid work in rural areas. Despite the egalitarian ideology of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> and the equality still promised in the Constitution, women have always been treated as second-class citizens in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. During <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s rule, when government and party committees on various levels were handpicked, one or two women would be put on them. Now there is limited choice in elections for such committees, and women are getting voted out.
</TEXT>
