<HEAD>Official Toll at 103 Dead In Train Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to update with death toll, compensation for
victims' families, comments of official saying he believes most
victims found, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Divers retrieved 13 more bodies today from a train that derailed on a bridge and tumbled into a lake, raising the death toll to 103, government and navy officials said. The divers used gas torches to cut open a last passenger car that could not be searched immediately after the accident on Friday. There had been fears that as many as 50 passengers were trapped in the car when it plunged into the water. But Vice Admiral <PERSON> Laxminarayan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramdas </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, said he believed most victims had been found. `` We have searched the entire lot,'' he said after returning from the accident scene. `` It is most unlikely that we will find any more bodies, though there may be odd ones stuck somewhere.'' However, teams of <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION> divers kept looking for bodies in the 20-to 30-foot water as far as 400 yards from the sunken wreckage. Railway Minister <PERSON> Madhav </PERSON> <PERSON> Rao </PERSON> <PERSON> Scindia </PERSON> today ordered a formal inquiry into the derailment. He told a news conference after visiting the crash site that families of victims would be compensated, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. Nine cars of the 14-car <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> derailed Friday on a bridge over <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asthamudi </LOCATION> near the town of <LOCATION> Quilon </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Kerala </LOCATION> state, about 1,200 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Latif </PERSON>, additional district magistrate in <LOCATION> Quilon </LOCATION>, said most victims died of drowning. At least 167 people remained hospitalized today, he said. Officials had said after the train wrecked that 500 people were injured, but most of the injured were treated for minor injuries and released. Efforts to recover the bodies continued into the night under floodlights, but had to be called off at 10 p.m. because of rain and poor visibility. The search resumed this morning. Six of the brick-red cars were partly or fully submerged in the water, and three hung from the bridge, which is about 15 feet above the lake. The engine and the following luggage car crossed the bridge safely, and the last four cars did not go off the trestle. Fishermen in long, narrow boats were the first to reach the scene, and the rescue official said they saved more than 200 people from drowning. The rescue official said 36 divers from the <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Cochin </LOCATION>, 70 miles northwest of the accident site, continued the rescue effort. The railway administration still does not know how many people were aboard the train bound from <LOCATION> Bangalore </LOCATION> in neighboring <LOCATION> Karnataka </LOCATION> state to <LOCATION> Trivandrum </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Kerala </LOCATION> and about 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Quilon </LOCATION>. Government television and Indian news agencies reported that a cave-in on the 540-foot bridge caused the derailment, but <ORGANIZATION> Railways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said the cause had yet to be determined. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, a railway safety official, said two spans of the bridge were damaged but that investigators believe this happened as the train cars plunged into the water. Witnesses told Indian news agencies that the train engineer jammed on the brakes just before the derailment. But <PERSON> Subramaniam </PERSON> said, `` It would n't cause a disaster of this magnitude.'' The Indian railway system, second largest in the world and carrying 9 million passengers daily, has been plagued with accidents. According to a report to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in February, 227 people were killed in 613 train accidents during 1987. The world's worst train accident occurred in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, according to the Guinness Book of World Records. More than 800 people were killed when a train plunged into a flood-swollen river in the eastern state of <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> in June 1981, <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> says.
