<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Calls For Sept. 1 Cease-Fire in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official today called for a Sept. 1 cease-fire in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and establishment of an interim Afghan government that would exclude guerrillas or officials under Marxist President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> envoy <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>, making his comments a a news conference after returning from the Afghan capital of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, said the proposed government would consist of `` recognized independent and impartial'' Afghans. <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said the new government would be effective Sept. 1, when a cease-fire would go into effect, and that it would convene a grand council of leaders no later than March 1. The grand council is a traditional Afghan decision-making body whose leaders were chosen according to the country's tribal structure. <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> said he believes such a council would be able to establish a government with broad-based support, while <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s national reconciliation plan and attempts by supporters of the guerrillas to generate mass support have failed The guerrillas did not immediately comment on <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>' peace plan, but a spokesman for a moderate guerrilla group opposed any negotiations with the communist Afghan government. `` We will not have anything to do with communists, any kind of communists,'' said <PERSON> Azim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nasser-Zia </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He also called for a `` cooling-off'' period in the fighting before Sept. 1, during which the interim government would be chosen. Afghan guerrilla leaders, backed by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, have insisted that they will cont