<HEAD>Growing Opposition Causes Tensions Within Mexico's Ruling Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS one graf for 21st graf pvs, ``Salinas' aides ...'' to
fix name of governing party. Pickup 22nd graf pvs, ``Salinas
campaigned ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Faced with its toughest opposition in years, the machine that runs <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is torn between adapting to a changing political climate or clinging to a formula that has kept it in power for six decades. The <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been beset by infighting between old-guard operatives who want to keep the system intact and a new breed led by presidential candidate <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, who want to modernize the party machine. The political system now is made up of a huge network of patronage and pork-barrel projects that can create or eliminate jobs, and which provide a raft of favors to loyal party members. Corruption has been a key ingredient in its succes. Under the system, the outgoing president usually names his successor, subject to approval by the party. Other candidates are chosen in closed conventions, and the party machinery makes sure they get elected. The system has kept the party in power under various names since it was formed in 1929. Its presidential candidate always has won with at least 70 percent of the vote. It has held the governors' offices in all of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 31 states and lost only one <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race, to a coalition that included the party. In the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, it has tolerated a weak opposition. Opponents or opposition groups who became to powerful often were bought off with plush jobs, or gradually swallowed by the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` For years it worked slowly, like an amoeba, assimilating and incorporating opposition groups,'' one old <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> hand, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said recently. As long as <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> remained even relatively prosperous, it could finance the party's system and the party kept <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> politically stable and generally content. The bubble burst in 1982, when prices of oil _ <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s principal export _ plunged, bringing on one of the severest economic crises in half a century Jobs suddenly were not plentiful. Real income plunged by at least 40 percent. One of the engineers of the austerity program was <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> di </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, 40, a Harvard-educated economist who served for five years as President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON>'s budget and planning secretary. The crisis also brought widespread discontent, and this strengthened the parties both on the right and the left of the governing party. The tensions between the old guard and the technocrats became more visible after <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' nomination for president last year. De la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> educated technocrat himself, ignored objections from powerful groups and selected <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> as his successor. Many favored <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, and others backed then-Energy and Mines Secretary <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Velazquez </PERSON>, 88, general secretary of the party's power <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> and a member of the old guard, made no bones of his displeasure when <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> was proclaimed by the party as its presidential candidate. Preliminary election figures from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> show the party won the presidency by its slimmest margin yet. Early returns indicate <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> won an estimated 47.4 percent, while <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON> of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> had 26.7 percent and <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clouthier </PERSON> of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had 20.7 percent. Even before Wednesday's elections, <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> said in his speeches the party should be modernized to meet the growing challenge of the opposition. The left's apparent success in the elections was spurred by <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, who broke with the governing party last year after his push for reforms was rebuffed. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' aides now speak of a `` multi-party system'' for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, in which the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> would occupy an expandable center. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> campaigned for democratic reforms, less state intervention in the economy and the need for `` clean elections.'' Aides said throughout the campaign that he was prepared to sacrifice ideology to practicality in a bid not just to get to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pinos </LOCATION>, the presidential residence, but to get there with some of his party's credibility intact. The major question for him in his first months of office will be how much resistance the `` old guard'' puts up to his proposed changes.
</TEXT>
