<HEAD>Pentagon Spokesman Gets Good Marks For Handling Iran Airliner
Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0519 to make keyword conform to digest</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-US Policy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pentagon spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> admits he is no expert on the high technology of the Iranian airliner crisis but, after more than 15 years in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, neither is he any stranger to dealing with reporters in times of trouble. For nearly 2 -LCB- hours during the past week, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> fielded questions in the cramped <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> briefing room about such things as transponders, air corridors, black boxes and the differences between Mode 2 and Mode 3 electronic signals. He had been a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> public affairs officer dealing with the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> when President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was forced from office. He had been spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> when <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> gunmen seized a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> airliner and killed <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>. He had been expelled from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for his contacts with Polish intellectuals after the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> government declared martial law in 1981. He had been a stand-in spokesman at the White House at the height of the Iran-Contra crisis. But nothing in his career had been quite like this. `` It's a very different environment from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said in an interview. `` Everybody has an opinion and a point of view, and the place is so big, there are so many points of view, there are so many kinds of experts, and not all those experts agree. ... And so we have the battle of the experts in the briefing room some of the time. `` The long-time news people here are the ones that, on some issues, it's very difficult to deal with, because you end up getting a counterbriefing from the floor.'' In the give-and-take, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> sometimes simply has told reporters that their questions go beyond his technical knowledge, saying, for example, `` I am not the final authority on widths of air corridors.'' `` I am simply trying to explain the matter the best I can with the information available to me,'' he said Thursday. Television, newspaper and magazine reporters covering the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> generally agree that he has done a good job, although to some he seemed a bit impatient at times. `` He gets testy over some things, as most any briefing officer does, but by and large he tries to be helpful,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rochelle </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. `` He tries to answer your questions. If he ca n't answer them, he tries to make it clear to you that he ca n't answer them, and sometimes he even tries to help when he ca n't answer.'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Voorst </PERSON>, national security correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I ` m amazed that <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> dares to stand up in front of that crowd out there, which is for the most part a pretty professional operation, and talk about Mode 2 or Mode 3 operations and that sort of stuff. He has obviously made every effort to at least become reasonably familiar with the technical issues he was talking about.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> correspondent of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I was very pleased on Tuesday that he took an hour to have, I think, a viable exchange with the assembled reporters.'' The twice-weekly <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> briefings usually last about half an hour. Tuesday's was roughly an hour and Thursday's was more than 80 minutes, almost entirely devoted to the shooting down of an Iranian Airbus by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruiser <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> on Sunday. `` This is not the kind of a story that any spokesman likes to deal with, of course, but all you can do is the best you can,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. The spokesman, 45, from <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, is married and has three children, the oldest a boy studying astronomy at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. His wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, a real estate agent, watched him brief on Thursday for the first time. Although he may not know everything about transponders, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, does have some technological expertise he can call upon. He is an old car buff, and likes to fix them up himself. The airliner incident and the current investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> procurement are the biggest stories he has had to handle since he came to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> in February as assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for public affairs from his previous post as a deputy White House press secretary. The week after the procurement story broke in mid-June, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> had planned to go on vacation. He has n't had the vacation yet.
