<HEAD>Bush's Vice Presidential, Campaign Staffs Sometimes At Odds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Because he is vice president as well as the certain Republican presidential nominee, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must contend with twin staffs. And insiders say the two sometimes-feuding factions have produced an ongoing tug-of-war over policy. A sharing of responsibility for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s daily activity between chief of staff <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> and campaign manager <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> is causing tensions within the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> operation, according to campaign officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. And while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has a committee of six trusted advisers to oversee the broad strokes of his campaign, advisers claim that turf battles are likely to continue until the vacant seat at the end of the table is occupied. That's the chair reserved for the still-unfilled post of campaign chairman, presumably being left open for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. `` At this point, with all due respect to everybody who's down there, the final decision-maker is not in the room,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> consultant <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign adviser. Although officials in recent days have made efforts to smooth over differences _ including a well-publicized strategy session last week among President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and top <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and campaign aides _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign workers still report some rough going in the coordination department. <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> is in charge of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign staff and oversees all political activity. <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, who works out of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s vice presidential office in the Old Executive Office Building and is on the public payroll, deals with the official vice presidential side of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s routine, including scheduling. However, insiders said that <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> has far more input over the entire <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> operation, including all details of campaign appearances and policy, than organizational charts might suggest. `` Fuller has got the keys,'' said a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign adviser familiar with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign operations. The adviser said <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> has enormous say on all matters dealing with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s schedule. And these days, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s schedule, not surprisingly, is mostly political. `` Often, it gets to be a real bureaucratic problem,'' said the adviser, who declined to be identified by name. <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> said no frictions exist and suggested that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign is well oiled. But officials in both offices claim privately that while <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> make a show of working together, there are many times when one side of the operation does n't know what the other side is doing. Frustrations about a lack of such coordination prompted the former campaign communications director, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Teeley </PERSON>, to quit his job in May. For one thing, until recently <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had two separate press staffs _ one answerable to <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, the other to <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>. Now, all campaign-related inquiries are fielded through the office of <PERSON> Shelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s new press secretary, who said she has `` unbridled input and access'' to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. One of her first acts was to put a halt to the mailing of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign speeches to news organizations by the office of the vice president _ at taxpayers' expense. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s senior communications adviser, said there still may be glitches, but fewer than before. `` Sometimes, the campaign may seem top heavy. But that's what's required if it's going to work. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> consultant, said that fragmented jurisdiction is not new with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign. `` The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> campaign had a lot of factions. I'm sure it's frustrating for everybody involved, but they both -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Atwater </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> -RRB- have valid perspectives.'' However, <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should `` leave the campaigning to <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> and the scheduling to <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>. Then they'll be in good shape.'' The campaign is overseen by a sort of board of directors, composed of <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, media consultant <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON>, pollster <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Teeter </PERSON> and two close friends of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mossbacher </PERSON>. The group meets, sometimes as frequently as once a week, to discuss strategy. According to <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, general concepts of the vice president's schedule are discussed at these meetings, but not the details, which he said are worked out between himself and <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, deputy to <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, said that `` we've done all right so far'' in seeking to coordinate the different roles of the office of vice president and the campaign office. In the meetings of the six campaign officials, `` everybody brings a unique set of responsibilities to the table,'' he said. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> is expected to join the campaign around the time of the Republican convention Aug. 15-18. Meanwhile, friction between an official staff and a campaign staff `` come with the territory'' when an incumbent is running either for re-election or for higher office, said <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> consultant <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON>. `` There are going to be misunderstandings, there is going to be confusion, there are going to be personality battles, there are going to be ego wars,'' <PERSON> Mahe </PERSON> said. `` But it will never be as brutal as it is to deal with an incumbent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator. Because at least here, the two staffs may be in different buildings but the buildings are only four blocks apart. When you've got an omnipotent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator's staff and a poor campaign staff out in the state someplace, then you have real double grief.''
