<BYLINE>By CARL C. CRAFT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rules out paying reparations to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s government but says the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is considering compensating families of the 290 people killed when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> shot down an Iranian jetliner. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says `` some form of humanitarian assistance would probably be appropriate.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the Republican presidential nominee-to-be, said Friday in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> he feels `` terribly sad for the families of those people'' who died in the downing of the Iranian passenger plane by an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> warship in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> last Sunday. `` I would never, ever under any circumstances offer reparations to the Iranian government,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. He added that he understands payments to the victims' families are being considered by the administration. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said the question of compensating the families is among matters `` under consideration.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said there were `` still some open questions'' on the compensation issue. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> indicated Friday in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> that he favors payments to the families. `` I think some form of humanitarian assistance would probably be appropriate,'' said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor and likely Democratic presidential nominee. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Republicans today via a telephone hookup that polls showing people think <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is more conservative than he is are `` crazy, nutty.'' Speaking from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, to mo