<HEAD>Shultz Arrives in Indonesia For Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds:UPDATES throughout with Shultz arrival in Indonesia, details
on Malaysian talks. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> officials and said he discussed human rights with Prime Minister <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> today during his last official trip to <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> for talks with President <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON> and other officials about informal talks scheduled July 25 in the <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> capital aimed at a political settlement of the Cambodian war. Earlier today, in the <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Kuala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lumpur </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> for three hours and said the <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> leader assured him prisoners detained without trial in <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> jails would be accorded their full rights. Twenty-eight <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen, the Washington-based Asia Watch human rights group and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> asked <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to bring up concerns over detentions under <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s Internal Security Act in his talks with <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON>, the two human rights groups said. The act allows the government to arrest and detain people without trial indefinitely. Last fall, the prime minister ordered the arrest of 106 people critical of his government _ including the leader of the opposition in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, Lim Kit Siang. He said then that their arrests were necessary because they had instigated racial clashes between the country's Malays and ethnic Chinese. `` The subject was discussed ... fundamentally in a satisfactory way,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, speaking to a news conference before leaving for <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. `` We took note that 71 people have been released and that the prime minister and foreign minister assured me that that those remaining under detention would be accorded full statutory and constitutional rights and as time went on we would see them dealt with properly,'' said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. But on Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Malaysian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> voted to strengthen the security act so that detainees can no longer challenge in court the reasons for their detention in court. When <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> became prime minister in July 1981, about 550 people were held without trial in Malaysian prisons. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, where he held talks with the foreign ministers of the member countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations. In <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, he was met at the military airport by the defense minister, Gen. L.B. <PERSON> Murdani </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> will hold talks with <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON> before leaving for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> Monday. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also will visit <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and new <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> republic in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> on the trip. <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> will be the host of informal talks between <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s Vietnam-backed government and three guerrilla groups The guerrillas have been fighting the government and Vietnamese troops since <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded in 1978.
