<HEAD>Zoning Error Leads 2 Couples To Build Modern Houses In Historic
District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One couple say they will fight an order to tear down their nearly complete modern house that was built in the town's historic district after the town mistakenly said the property was zoned residential. A second couple are considering a similar fight. The zoning board voted unanimously Thursday to deny <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> and <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Sallah </PERSON> an exception to the zoning ordinance because the shape and vertical siding of their silo-shaped house are not compatible with other buildings in the district. <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, lawyer for the couple, said she would seek a second hearing, and will go to court if the board does not change its mind. She said state law says such zoning decisions can only be made by historic district commissioners, and <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION> has none. Another couple, <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Desmarais </PERSON>, said they were considering a suit against the town after they were told they would have to modify the ranch house they are building. Their house also is nearly complete. Both couples applied for building permits earlier this year, and the building inspector told them the property was zoned residential. Later, members of the zoning board later acknowledged that the town zoning map was erroneous, but maintained that the historic district and its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> style of architecture should be preserved. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinter </PERSON>, chairman of the planning board who wanted to halt the building, and building inspector <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, who favored allowing the building, both resigned over the dispute. The Sallahs paid $ 75,000 for their 3.7 acres less than one mile from the center of the town of about 1,500, and are building the house from a kit valued at $ 50,000. The circular part is two stories with a more conventional one-story attachment. Board member <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Brillhart </PERSON> said compensation may be the only solution. Board Chairman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Halla </PERSON> said a decision on compensation would be left to the town selectmen. Selectman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> said he did n't think the Sallahs should pay for the town's mistake, but he did not offer compensation. <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> expressed frustration with the town's architectural conservatism. `` If everybody had built houses that look exactly alike, we'd still be living in wigwams,'' she said `` You need to allow for change and variety.''
