<HEAD>Second Step Taken In Rehabilitation of Bukharin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party has readmitted <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON>, a major Bolshevik theorist, and more than a dozen others shot during purges under <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> a half-century ago, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday. <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> had been cleared in February of trumped-up spying charges for which he was shot in 1938. But the second step in his rehabilitation, restoration to party rolls, was not taken until now. Political rehabilitation had been expected, because <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON>'s moderate economic program contains elements similar to those being implemented by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikahil </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> But in today's <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> announcement, the official news agency said a special commission of the party's ruling Politburo found that <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> and an associate, <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON>, had made mistakes. `` However, their mistakes and dissenting positions are not of an anti-party character,'' the commission said. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> dispatch did not detail the mistakes <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON> had made. In the 1920s, <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> favored a continuation of Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s New Economic Policy, which permitted some private enterprise and left farms in the hands of the peasants. <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> hoped to encourage farmers to combine property voluntarily and move onto collective farms. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms also allow some private enterprise and families to lease farmland from their collective and state farms and till the soil themselves. Last November, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announced that the drive to rehabilitate the millions of victims of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges would resume. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> ruled from 1924 to his death in 1953. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the Politburo commission heard a report from the party control committee saying <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON>, expelled from the party in March 1937, were readmitted June 21. The news agency did not explain why it took 2 -LCB- weeks to announce the action. Fourteen other victims of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges who had been tried along with <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rykov </PERSON> were also restored to party rolls, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said.
