<HEAD>Parliament Tightens Law On Detention Without Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with Shultz visit, comments on human
rights. Pickup 4th pvs, ``The official ...'' Minor editing
thereafter to TRIM and CONFORM</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House of Representatives voted to strengthen the Internal Security Act, which allows the government to arrest and detain people without trial indefinitely. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the law Friday and sent it to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> today and said he discussed human rights issues with Prime Minister <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON>. Last fall, the prime minister ordered the arrest of 106 people critical of his government _ including the leader of the opposition in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, Lim Kit Siang. <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> said then that their arrests were necessary because they had instigated racial clashes between the country's Malays and ethnic Chinese. `` The subject was discussed ... fundamentally in a satisfactory way,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said at a news conference before leaving for <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. `` We took note that 71 people have been released and that the prime minister and foreign minister assured me that that those remaining under detention would be accorded full statutory and constitutional rights and as time went on we would see them dealt with properly,'' said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. Twenty-eight <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen, the Washington-based Asia Watch human rights group and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> had asked <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to bring up American concerns over the detentions with <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON>, according to the two human rights groups. The official <ORGANIZATION> Bernama </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported that the amendments passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, among other things, `` prohibited any action, suit, prosecution, or any other legal proceedings from being brought, instituted or maintained in respect of any detention.'' Forty-seven representatives supported the amendments and 18 were opposed. The amendments will go to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for approval later this month and then to the king before they become law. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is dominated by government appointees, and the king, like <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, is a constitutional head and normally signs all laws passed by the legislature. `` By completely depriving the right of the people to seek legal redress in court, the situation is worse than during the colonial days,'' former foreign minister <PERSON> Rais </PERSON> <PERSON> Yatim </PERSON>, a governing party member who opposes <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON>, said during the parliamentary debate. <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> won independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1957 and inherited the Internal Security Act from the days of colonial rule. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> Thai, acting leader of the parliamentary opposition, said the amendments would prohibit anyone who has been improperly detained from asking a court to secure his release. Deputy Home Affairs Minister <PERSON> Megat </PERSON> <PERSON> Junid </PERSON> <PERSON> Megat </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayub </PERSON> said during the debate the government would not abuse its powers and that the Internal Security Act was necessary for the security of the country. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen and human rights groups have called for the detainees to be brought to trial or released. About 80 people now are being held under the act. When <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> became prime minister in July 1981, more than 500 people were under detention.
