<HEAD>Unions Point To Firings, Suspensions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> union leaders say a new safety agreement with the carrier could be a sign of progress, but add that tense labor-management relations will improve more if the high number of firings and suspensions is reduced. `` We've had five terminations this week, so nothing has abated,'' said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Currier </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> local representing 7,000 flight attendants. The rate of firings `` is far higher than it was last year, and far higher than it was before -LRB- Frank -RRB- <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>. `` It would be one of the most meaningful areas for improvement.'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> took over Eastern more than two years ago, inheriting some $ 2.5 billion in debts and a recent history of labor-management conflict. At the district office of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest with 12,000 mechanics, baggage handlers and ramp workers, union officials keep detailed charts tracing the steady rise of disciplinary measures, particularly firings, since the takeover `` Our big concern is the unjust terminations. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> talks about mending fences, but I do n't think the word has filtered down to his front-line management, who keep burning bridges,'' said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacino </PERSON>, a Machinists general chairman. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> would n't comment on the safety agreement announced Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> beyond a statement from President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON>. While Bakes praised the agreement as important to separating safety from other issues, he said a `` missing link'' remains until contract negotiations are completed with the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>, who have been in federal mediation for seven months, and the pilots, with whom talks started about a month ago. Former Labor Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, who brought the two sides together in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said battling between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management and its union leadership threatens the carrier's survival. `` It is the commitment of labor and management leaders which will make or break this effort,'' <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said. `` Frankly, this presents some cause for concern.'' `` All observers have said when looking at this that they've never seen anything this severe and such shrill treatment between management and labor _ maybe going back to the'40s and the coal miners,'' said veteran Machinists leader <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> The agreement calls for more outside, impartial scrutiny, increased communications between labor and management, and promises no reprisals against employees who point out safety problems. The Machinists claim that employees who balked at hurry-up work have been disciplined; in addition, workers have been fired for insubordination, refusing to work excessive overtime or for union activities. The <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union has had 41 shop stewards fired in the last two years. This year, 129 Machinists have been fired so far, compared to 157 in the first six months of 1987, the union says. The Machinists say they have fared well in grievances, winning back pay and reinstatement in a majority of cases. But the grievance procedures are backlogged more than a year, they say. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, representing 3,500 Eastern pilots, has had a different problem: many of its pilots have gone to other airlines or left the industry entirely because of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s tense situation and uncertain future. Pilots spokesman <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said nearly 1,000 pilots will have left <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> since 1986 by the end of this summer, according to projections. `` You're talking about 25 percent. Without the pilots, these planes are taco stands,'' <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said. Pilots last year launched a MaxSafety program in which they highlighted alleged safety laxity and took their complaints into congressional hearings. Eastern has said toughened absenteeism policies and increased discipline are part of efforts to correct years of worker abuses that have driven up costs. Management has indicated it still believes cuts in labor costs are essential. This spring, federal officials conducted special inspections of aircraft flown by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, another <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. They also examined <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s management and finances. They said that they found no unsafe conditions but warned of possible safety problems because of the labor-management battles.
