<HEAD>Newspaper Reports 2,000 More Cuban Troops In Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Portuguese newspaper reported Saturday that 2,000 Cuban troops have been sent to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to bolster government defenses near the border with <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The independent weekly Expresso quoted unidentified reliable sources as saying the Cubans, described as experts in mounting and firing missiles, landed in the former <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> colony in June. The newspaper said the reinforcements were sent to strengthen the position of the Marxist Angolan government and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> in negotiations with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to end the 13-year civil war in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The reinforcements arrived shortly before a second round of peace negotiations between the four countries in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, the newspaper said. Lower level delegations scheduled more talks Monday and Tuesday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In a separate story, Expresso quoted unidentified diplomatic sources in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> as saying <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> forces had mounted a defensive line involving 26,000 men in the south of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, close to South African-administered <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> have acknowledged that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> began sending reinforcements of elite troops to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in November to help the 35,000 Cuban soldiers already stationed there contain South African advances in the south. Western analysts believe those reinforcements brought the number of Cubans in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to about 46,000. Expresso claimed the Cuban reinforcements were creating differences between the Angolan government and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Last week, <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Risquet </PERSON>, the chief Cuban negotiator at the peace talks, strongly denied any rift. He told a news conference in <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> all military decisions were made by the Angolan government. South African troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> support guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, also backed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, who have been fighting since 1975 to force the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> - and Cuban-supported government to share power A peace settlement turns on securing a withdrawal of foreign troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and implementing a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution to make <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independent.
