<HEAD>Lockheed Closing Plant Opened in Wake of 1965 Watts Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The closing of a <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant will end one of the few successful efforts by a major employer to create jobs in the impoverished <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION> neighborhood following the 1965 riots. The Watts-Willowbrook plant, which makes parts for the C-5 cargo plane, will close by October when work on the C-5 is completed, the company said Friday. The plant is on the city's south side, about 8 miles from downtown. Of the plant's 117 workers, 78 have enough seniority to qualify for transfers to the company's <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION> plant, about 20 miles away. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> said it will attempt to find employment for the rest with other aerospace firms. A <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the company had expected to use the plant for other work after the completion of the C-5 program, but <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s aircraft business has been dwindling and no suitable projects could be found. `` We had hoped that <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> would be able to feed more work to Watts-Willowbrook,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Molli </PERSON>, an aide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif. `` We want to see that the workers are taken care of. Former <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Kotchian </PERSON> recalled in a recent interview that the company's decision to open the plant four years after the devastating riot was considered controversial. `` I had my own people take issue with me,'' <PERSON> Kotchian </PERSON> said. `` They said I was going to spend a lot of money and the place was going to be run down and there was going to be thievery and muggings at the plant. None of it came to pass.'' Instead, the plant matched the productivity and efficiency of most Lockheed factories, he said. The arrest of a black man by a state highway patrol officer on Aug. 11, 1965, touched off a week of rioting that turned <PERSON> Watts </PERSON> into a national symbol of racial strife. Thirty-four people died in the riot and 4,000 people were arrested. Damage from the six days of looting, fires and shooting reached $ 40 million. <ORGANIZATION> DV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, a smaller aerospace company that has operated in <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION> for 30 years, plans to take over <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s 25-year lease on the factory, which is owned by <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit group formed after the riot. The company expects to double its 55-person work force over the next year and will give hiring preference to former <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> workers, said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON>, DV's executive vice president. <ORGANIZATION> DV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, a privately held company with sales under $ 10 million per year, inspects and paints aircraft parts for <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and other aerospace firms.
