lace officials to protect the cleanliness of the election,'' <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamente </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>, said. `` The country is changing ... very broad sectors went to vote even though they knew'' there would be the traditional fraud, something that kept them away in the past, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrido </PERSON>, a political analyst who wrote a book on the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, said. `` They went to vote for another system.'' <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, academic director of the <ORGANIZATION> Colegio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, a think tank and graduate school, said the change was long in coming. `` From 1940 to 1988 you ca n't see many political changes,'' he said. But in the same half century, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> evolved from a sparsely inhabited rural country whose people had little education to a fast-growing urban nation with schools and well developed communications. A <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> official says the answer in the <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> administration will be to `` play by clean rules, and on economic issues you deliver.'' <PERSON> Castaneda </PERSON>, reflecting a view expressed by others, said the election `` means the end of the one-party system and also the end of a situation where the government could do what it wanted.'' But <PERSON> Garrido </PERSON> said he believed the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>'s assurance of a majority in the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would keep the opposition from influencing the government and still allow <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> to carry out h