<BYLINE>Changes In Robeson County: Are They Real Or Cosmetic?
^By ERICA JOHNSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five months after two American Indians took hostages at a newspaper to protest local conditions, changes have been made to address their concerns, but some say it remains to be seen whether the reforms will bring lasting change. Others say the real change is that residents of <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> have realized `` that they can control their lives.'' `` It's truly cosmetic,'' <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> said last week of the changes, which include a second superior court judgeship and a task force named by Gov. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> to investigate alleged corruption in the county. `` It's nothing more than to douse the fire, hoping it will go out,'' said <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>, one of two Lumbee Indian men who entered the offices of The Robesonian newspaper Feb. 1, allegedly armed, in what they said was a protest of local corruption and discrimination against minorities. The daylong siege ended when the governor agreed to appoint the task force. The county's population of about 100,000 is 37 percent Indian, 37 percent white and 26 percent black. The Rev. <PERSON> Mac </PERSON> <PERSON> Legerton </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION>, also was cautious. `` The policy changes which have occurred relate to the administration of the law,'' he said. `` Hopefully, these changes will provide better treatment under the law. But they will not ensure justice throughout <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.'' Other residents were more optimistic. `` From my point of view, we got the second judgeship, and we're going to get a public defender,'' said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON>, a Lumbee community leader who led <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s campaign for superior court judge `` That's pretty good,'' <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON> said. `` But we're making sure that people do n't forget and do n't let up. We're taking care of business.'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, a Lumbee who was running against District Attorney <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> for <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s superior court judgeship, was shot to death in March in what initially was called an assassination but was later termed a domestic dispute. That left the post to <PERSON> Britt </PERSON>, who has sent more people to death row than any other prosecutor in the nation. After it became apparent that the judgeship would go to <PERSON> Britt </PERSON>, the state agreed to create a second judgeship, which would go to a member of a minority group. <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> said the second judgeship `` was just to appease the people of <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, hoping that the people will die down.'' Because <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> is expected to be the county's senior judge, he `` will be able to set the -LRB- judicial -RRB- calendar, pick a magistrate, and set the bail-bond policy,'' <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> said. `` What have we gained? Nothing.'' But <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> said real change has come in the minds of Lumbee Indians and blacks. `` The people have seen changes in themselves because they have realized that they can control their lives,'' he said. `` Now it's not just me and -LRB- fellow accused hostage-taker <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> -RRB- speaking out,'' <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> said. `` Now it's the poor farmer, it's the grass-roots people. They're realizing they can do something. They're unaccustomed to politically fighting back. But they're beginning to.'' He cited a referendum vote to unite the county's five-school system that passed by a razor-thin margin this spring. Supporters say it will lessen economic and educational disparities among schools in the system and foster a sense of common purpose. <PERSON> Godwin </PERSON> agreed that many people in <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> who previously have felt powerless now feel differently. `` People are angry, but the point is, they realize that they can do something about it,'' he said. `` I think people are going to take advantage of that, especially the younger people.'' `` It used to be we were just lost,'' said <PERSON> Georgeanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavis </PERSON>, 66. `` Now, it seems that we are coming out.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Chavis </PERSON> also said she thought whites have treated her better in recent months. `` Maybe they feel that we're trying to pull ourselves out of where we were,'' she said. `` It's like white people are saying ` We do n't see why they waited so long.''' Would those changes have come about without the protest <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> staged? `` I think they certainly can be given credit,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a leader of Concerned Citizens and vice-chairman of the county's human-relations commission. `` We do n't approve of their means. But I think they gave us the impetus for change in <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.''
