<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> began Saturday to partially dismantle its old-guard leadership, but it has yet to decide how much new blood to inject into its top ranks. The party removed 10 of the 31 members of the policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, including five who are in their 80s. The 10 were named to the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, an honorary supervisory group of mostly retired officials. Nationalist leaders have stressed the importance of promoting younger members of the party, known as the Kuomingtang, which was formed 94 years ago on the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> mainland and has for four decades claimed to be the sole rightful ruler of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Party spokesman <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tai </PERSON> told reporters that the new <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will be named Thursday at the end of the weeklong 13th party congress. A Cabinet overhaul is expected later. Most of the aging leaders in the current <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> _ whose members' average age is 70 _ fled to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> from the Chinese mainland in 1949, when <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON> and his Nationalist government were routed by the Communists. These older Nationalists still hold a majority of seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and support the party's claim that it has the right to govern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The personnel changes are likely to determine the pace for continuing the liberalization program started by President <PERSON> Chiang </PERSO