<HEAD>State Threatens To Revoke Insurance Company's License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An insurance company faces revocation of its license in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> if it refuses to issue drought-insurance policies to about 1,000 farmers who paid for more than $ 40 million in coverage, a state official says. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Commerce Commissioner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said Friday that New Jersey-based <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> informed farmers who paid for the policies by a June 15 deadline that the policies will not be issued. But under a 1987 state law, once an insurance agent accepts and cashes a check from a farmer, the policy can not be canceled by either party, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. All checks were cashed by June 15, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. `` We've told the company that we want the policies issued,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. `` We're saying if you do n't issue the policies, we'll ask the attorney general's office to prepare documents to revoke'' the company's license to do business in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said a meeting is scheduled Monday between state officials and company representatives. Company officials did not return telephone calls seeking comment. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> had told <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> insurance agents that the sales should be canceled and premiums refunded to buyers, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. The company explained that sales exceeded its capacity. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> was remiss for deciding halfway through a drought-stricken summer to refund premiums on drought coverage. When the issue first arose last week, <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> contended that it had taken applications that did n't translate into coverage until it approved them. Some of the applications contain such a statement and others do n't, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. The insurance would begin paying buyers a percentage of the full amount if rainfall fell below 70 percent of normal at the nearest official rain gauge during June, July and August. The lower the rainfall, the higher the amount paid.
