<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said U.S.-backed rebels twice attacked troops Saturday in violation of a government-declared cease-fire, killing two soldiers in one attack and losing four dead in another. The ministry said in a statement that the rebels, known as Contras, killed two soldiers, wounded one and captured four others in a morning ambush about 90 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> in the province of <LOCATION> Matagalpa </LOCATION>. In another incident in a remote region near the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast, four rebels were killed when they attacked Sandinista troops, the statement said. The government has declared a unilateral cease-fire until July 31 to allow time to restart stalled peace talks. A fragile truce has been in effect since March 21, but no new sessions of talks have been scheduled to end the nearly 7-year-old war between the Contras and the leftist Sandinista regime. The Contras agreed to go along with the latest cease-fire as long as they were n't attacked. Saturday's <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement was the latest in a series of government charges that the rebels are ignoring the truce. It said Defense Minister <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has asked a monitoring commission set up after the first round of talks to verify a rebel attack July 4 in the Chontales province. The government says 12 soldiers and civilians were killed in that attack. The Sandinistas came to power in July 1979 after 42 years of rule by the rightist, pro-U.S. government of <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>.
