<HEAD>LaserPhoto LAR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight members of a convoy carrying aid to Nicaraguan civilians were arrested Saturday during a melee after they tried to cross a bridge into <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The scuffle broke out on the international bridge when officers sprayed a cayenne-based irritant into the truck of the Veterans Peace Convoy, which had blocked a traffic lane for four hours. Police arrested the eight as 50 of their supporters chanted, `` The whole world is watching!'' and rushed past a line of police at the bridge toll booth that separates the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Customs officers said allowing the trucks to leave the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> without assurances they would be returned would violate a trade embargo against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The convoy, which had tried to cross the same bridge a month ago, had intended to take 17 vehicles into <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> at noon Saturday. Two trucks were driven to the toll booth where Customs officers and police stopped them. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON>, acting chief Customs inspector, told <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Livesey </PERSON>, driver of the convoy's lead pickup, that he could not allow him to turn onto the Mexico-bound lane. `` This is as far as you're going to get,'' <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON> told <PERSON> Livesey </PERSON>. `` You can turn north -LRB- back to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> -RRB- here if you want.'' <PERSON> Livesey </PERSON> responded: `` We're not moving. ... We're either going to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> here _ this is a free border _ or we're going to jail. He then placed several boxes of baby food on the hood of his car and refused to budge. Four hours later, police again told the trucks' occupants they must move the vehicles or be arrested. The trucks stayed put, and officers stuck a nightstick into a window of a truck driven by <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Meserve </PERSON>, 45, of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The window shattered as <PERSON> Meserve </PERSON> tried to roll it up. Officers simultaneously sprayed the cab with the substance laced with cayenne, a very hot, irritating spice. About 50 supporters of the convoy had been watching and rushed past officers as the arrests began. Some started pounding on a convoy truck, shouting, `` The whole world is watching!'' <PERSON> Livesey </PERSON>, 46, a <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veteran from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Meserve </PERSON> were among those arrested. `` There was a little bit of pushing and shoving but there was nothing where anybody was in any real, serious danger,'' said Police Chief <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>. Once the arrests were made, the crowd began following officers' orders and moved back, he said. Police towed the convoy's pickup trucks off the bridge, and traffic across it was restored to normal soon afterward.
