<SECOND>AM-Ireland-Pubs,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Averted at Dublin Pubs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bartenders on Saturday approved a settlement with pub owners over a pay dispute that developed after the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> passed new laws to extend pub hours. The laws, approved last month in an effort to accommodate the tourist industry, came into operation smoothly in the rest of the country but in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> the bartenders demanded extra pay and threatened to strike Saturday morning. The 3,000 union bartenders in the city earn an average $ 300 a week and wanted $ 45 a week more and an extra half day off every two weeks if they were going to work the new hours, which would increase their 40-hour work week by an hour. Publicans offered a one-time `` goodwill payment'' of $ 150 to bartenders with more than six months' service, and an extra $ 18 a week. Union leaders recommended acceptance of the offer and barmen approved it by a vote of 628 to 539. There are about 750 pubs in the city area _ about 500 of them employing union members. The rest of the pubs are run by families and have been operating the new hours. The pubs used to close at 11:30 p.m. in summer and 11 p.m. in winter, Monday through Saturday. Now they can close at midnight in summer and 11:30 in winter. They get an extra hour Sunday, closing at 11 instead of 10 p.m. The one-hour afternoon closure between 2:30 and 3:30 p.m., in effect in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Cork </PERSON> only, also has been eliminated. The main aim of the new laws was to answer complaints from the tourist industry that visitors thought closing time was too early.
</TEXT>
