 scheduled, but he expected negotiations to resume early in September. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation official, speaking on condition of anonymity, put the value of present annual grain sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> at about $ 1.5 billion. <PERSON> Holmer </PERSON> said he hoped that before the Soviet negotiations chief, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chumakov </PERSON>, goes on vacation on July 25, `` we will know when and where and whether there will be another round of discussions.'' <PERSON> Holmer </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting had been useful and `` we made considerable progress in a number of areas. ... But differences still remain.'' The two sides now are now at a stage where they need to review their positions with their governments, said <PERSON> Holmer </PERSON>, who met reporters at his hotel.
