<HEAD>Banks Warned Against Slowing Growth in Debtor Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> cautioned participating banks on Friday that failure to upgrade aid to the debtor nations would slow their financial growth. `` Unless the banks do more to support adjustment efforts of middle-income counties, the notion that our debt strategy is a collaborative one oriented to growth will not pass serious scrutiny,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> said. `` Indeed, it will prevent the resumption of an adequate rate of growth, and all sides will lose,'' he said in a speech prepared for a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> endorsed agreements between the debtor nations and creditors for new arrangements to reduce the estimated $ 1.2 trillion debt of certain Third World. The nations with the largest debts are in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> _ where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks are the largest lenders. He expressed concern over difficulties in developing loan packages for those governments trying to adjust to their international debt problems. Such packages usually include loans by the fund itself, by commercial banks and by intergovernmental lenders like the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Adjustments required in return for the loans generally include austerity programs that debtor governments find difficult. <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> said programs to adjust debtor countries to a better handling of their funds will in many cases have costs in the short run but will eventually help their citizens and particularly the poor. `` The poor would almost certainly suffer much more in the absence of corrective action,'' he said, noting that `` the poor can be protected, at least to some degree by compensatory measures.'' <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> noted that some adjustment measures are of immediate help to some poor people, such as increased prices for farm products that help the poor in rural areas.
