<HEAD>Inflation Reaches 41.3 Percent for First Half of 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices rose 41.3 percent for the first half of 1988, the business daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiero </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. It tabulated the figures from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement that inflation rose 2 percent in June, slightly above the 1.9 percent increase in May. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Financiero </PERSON>'s report noted that despite an increase in June, figures for both months were the lowest registered since November 1981. Inflation has been reduced by an Economic Solidarity Pact designed by the government in December and endorsed by business and labor. Consumer prices hit a record 159.2 percent last year. President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> announced the program after officials became worried that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was on the verge of spiraling into hyperinflation, a problem that has plagued other Latin American countries. Critics say the pact was intended to artificially control inflation before Wednesday's general elections. The president concludes his six-year term on Nov. 30, with his successor virtually certain to be <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that has governed <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> since 1929. The budget and planning secretary, <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON>, said Wednesday that it will be up to the next administration to decide if the pact continues past November. He told reporters that the agreement remains in effect at least through August and that its status for the last three months of <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madrid </ORGANIZATION>'s term wo n't be determin