<HEAD>Some Commodity Markets Cooling Down After Ride On Drought Train</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 After weeks of playing follow-the-soybeans, traders in a number of commodity markets are looking elsewhere for signals on whether to buy or sell. Some of these markets, such as gold and sugar, have only a marginal interest in grain and soybean prices to begin with. Others _ cotton in particular _ have almost no real relationship to soybeans and are cooling down after a frantic ride on the drought train, courtesy of market speculators. The Midwestern drought remains the dominant influence in the grain and soybean markets and in the livestock markets, where the price of feed grain is directly related to production costs. But the drought's diminishing impact on the prices of other commodities illustrates how the powerful psychology of a runaway market can sweep others along with it _ until the facts get in the way. `` In the end, the fundamentals always reign supreme,'' said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, cotton specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In the cotton market, the fundamentals include the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s prediction of a 5.6 million-bale surplus on July 31, the end of the current marketing year, and a whopping 6.8 million-bale surplus a year later. There is nearly enough cotton in storage to fulfill all of next year's expected domestic demand, twice as much as experts consider adequate. Before the drought began, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimated 1988-89 cotton production at 14 million bales. Analysts say even severe drought damage would n't reduce the oversupply. `` We could lose 2 -LCB- million bales and not be hurt,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitten </PERSON>, cotton specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. So why did near-month cotton futures follow the soybean market's sharp springtime surge, rallying from about 60 cents a pound on April 15 to almost 70 cents by June 20 `` Cotton very often is called soybean's little brother,'' <PERSON> Whitten </PERSON> said. `` It follows it slavishly.'' Added <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantor </PERSON>, cotton analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>: `` It was n't so much the fabulous buying that brought the prices up, it was that you did n't have anybody willing to sell it. That allowed the speculative element to move prices higher in tandem with the other markets.'' Cotton futures prices have since come back down to around 60 cents a pound. `` People finally became convinced the fundamentals had been ignored too long, said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. The inflation-sensitive gold market followed a similar, albeit shorter path. In early June, gold for August delivery surged above its recent $ 440-to - $ 460 trading range to more than $ 470 a troy ounce The accepted explanation was that traders feared the sharp rise in grain prices would lead to greater inflation. Those worries were quickly calmed by economists, who pointed out the miniscule impact of food prices on the Consumer Price Index, and gold prices eased back into their well-worn trading range. `` The soybean market and the rally we had in previous weeks certainly constituted a psychological inducement to rally the precious metals. But in general you have to keep the advance in perspective,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON>, metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The gold market indicated ... that food-inspired increases alone were not going to boost inflation rates to dangerously high levels.'' In fact, commodity markets almost never take their direction from a single source and single-day moves often have no easy explanation, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Chronowitz </PERSON>, director of futures research for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The media naturally wants to know why gold is up a dollar today or why it's down a dollar,'' he said. `` Sometimes there is no reason. But when they're at a loss to explain a move, analysts will tend to tie it to something else.''
</TEXT>
