<HEAD>Low Unemployment Rate Raises Inflation Fears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Droves of teen-agers on summer employment rolls helped push the nation's unemployment rate to a 14-year low in June, but the news rekindled inflation fears and sent stock and bond prices tumbling. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday before trading began on Wall Street that the unemployment rate for June stood at 5.3 percent. The unexpectedly strong report sent the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials down 16.54 points to a close at 2,106.15 in light trading. Concern that inflation might rise as the economy heats up also rippled through the credit markets, where the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year issue fell about $ 10 per $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield jumped to 9.09 percent from 9.00 percent late Thursday. But the unemployment report was welcomed in the currency markets, where the dollar jumped despite central bank intervention. Traders reasoned that a big reported rise in manufacturing employment was an indication that exports remained strong, which could help shrink the trade deficit and support the dollar. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the sharp drop from May's 5.6 percent jobless rate was caused by a seasonally adjusted surge of 820,000 people _ three-fourths of them youths 16 to 24 years old _ onto the nation's payrolls. Joblessness among black youths plummeted more than 6 percentage points to its lowest level on record. Analysts had anticipated a large increase this year in the number of available summer jobs, especially in the tourist industry, as foreigners taking advantage of the devalued dollar flock to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for their vacations. In other economic developments Friday: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> reported that Americans increased their installment borrowing at a modest annual rate of 4.6 percent in May, as growth in consumer credit slowed from the rapid expansion of earlier this year Consumers took out $ 2.42 billion more in credit than they paid off in May, compared with net growth of $ 3.85 billion in April. _ Oil futures turned mixed in moderate trading as dealers reassessed the impact of the recent <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil rig explosion on petroleum supplies and prospects for an emergency <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting diminished On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the contract for August delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, fell 37 cents to $ 15.46 per 42-gallon barrel.
</TEXT>
