<HEAD>Oil Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures gave up some of their recent gains as dealers reassessed the impact of the recent <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil rig explosion on petroleum supplies and prospects for an emergency <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting diminished. `` It may be a case of calmer heads prevailing today,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an oil analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said of Friday's trading session Prices for petroleum futures and contracts for refined products had soared on Thursday as traders reacted to reports that the <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> rig explosion would affect about 12 percent of total <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> production, or as much as 300,000 barrels of oil per day. In addition, there was concern that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> countries might call an emergency meeting to discuss overproduction among some of its members. `` I think they over-reacted to the effects of the platform fire and they realized it really did n't mean that much ... and the gains were given back,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON>, an energy analsyt with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` I think the market also realized there was n't going to be an emergency meeting.'' As a result, he said, Friday's trading was highlighted by profit-taking and a general correction from Thursday's overbought condition. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the contract for August delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> crude oil fell 37 cents to $ 15.46 per 42-gallon barrel after closing 47 cents higher on Thursday. The contract had traded well above $ 16 during that session. Among refined products traded on the exchange, home heating oil fell 0.90 cent to 43.39 cents a gallon. Unleaded gasoline rose 0.05 cent to 53.17 cents a gallon. Analysts attributed the slight rise to reports of strong seasonal demand.
